2 HOUSE BILL 222
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
4 Article – Education
5 Section 11–1202 through 11–1204
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Education
11 7–411.
12 (a) The State Board shall develop and implement a program of drug addiction and
13 prevention education in the public schools.
14 (b) (1) Except as provided in subsection (c)(2) of this section, this program shall
15 be started before the sixth grade in each public school by teachers who are trained in the
16 field of drug education.
17 (2) The State Board shall establish standards for determining how a
18 teacher is considered to be “trained in the field of drug addiction and prevention education”
19 for the purposes of this section.
20 (c) (1) The program shall include instruction related to heroin and opioid
21 addiction and prevention, including information relating to the lethal effect of fentanyl AND
22 THE MITIGATING EFFECTS OF NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
23 MEDICATIONS.
24 (2) The instruction required under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall
25 be:
26 (i) Delivered in grade bands as follows:
27 1. Third grade through fifth grade;
28 2. Sixth grade through eighth grade; and
29 3. Ninth grade through twelfth grade; and
30 (ii) A stand–alone unit in the program.
31 (d) This program shall be coordinated with other State agencies that are
32 responsible for drug abuse education and control.

HOUSE BILL 222 3
1 7–426.5.
2 (a) Each county board shall establish a policy in accordance with school health
3 guidelines and State laws and regulations for public schools within its jurisdiction to
4 authorize [the school nurse, school health services personnel, and other school personnel]
5 AN INDIVIDUAL ACTING IN GOOD FAITH, AND A HIGH SCHOOL STUDENT IN
6 ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION to administer naloxone or other
7 OPIOID overdose–reversing medication to a student or other person located on school
8 property who is reasonably believed to be experiencing an opioid overdose.
9 (b) (1) The policy established under subsection (a) of this section shall include:
10 (1) (I) A provision requiring all public schools to obtain and store at the
11 public school naloxone or other OPIOID overdose–reversing medication to be used in an
12 emergency situation; [and]
13 (2) (II) A requirement that each public school develop and implement a
14 method for notifying the parents or guardians of students of the school’s policy under this
15 section at the beginning of each school year; AND
16 (3) (III) AUTHORIZATION FOR A HIGH SCHOOL STUDENT, A MEMBER
17 OF THE SCHOOL’S STAFF, OR ANY LAWFULLY PRESENT INDIVIDUAL AT THE SCHOOL
18 OR A SCHOOL–SPONSORED EVENT OR ACTIVITY WHO HAS RECEIVED TRAINING ON
19 THE APPROPRIATE USE OF NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
20 MEDICATION TO POSSESS NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
21 MEDICATION.
22 (2) THE POLICY ESTABLISHED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS
23 SECTION MAY INCLUDE A RECORD OF STUDENTS WHO INTEND TO POSSESS
24 NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING MEDICATION AND WHETHER
25 THOSE STUDENTS HAVE RECEIVED APPROPRIATE TRAINING.
26 (c) Except for any willful or grossly negligent act, any [of the following individuals
27 who respond] INDIVIDUAL WHO RESPONDS in good faith to the overdose emergency of a
28 student, A SCHOOL STAFF MEMBER, OR ANY OTHER INDIVIDUAL LAWFULLY PRESENT
29 AT A SCHOOL in accordance with this section may not be held personally liable for any act
30 or omission in the course of responding to the emergency[:
31 (1) A school nurse;
32 (2) Other school health services personnel who are licensed or certified to
33 practice a health occupation under the Health Occupations Article; or
34 (3) Other school personnel; OR

4 HOUSE BILL 222
1 (4) A HIGH SCHOOL STUDENT WHO HAS RECEIVED TRAINING ON THE
2 APPROPRIATE USE OF NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
3 MEDICATION].
4 (d) (1) The county board or the local health department shall, by local
5 agreement:
6 (i) Hire a sufficient number of either county or regional community
7 action officials; or
8 (ii) Develop and implement a program that provides the community
9 relations and education functions required to be conducted by community action officials in
10 paragraph (2) of this subsection.
11 (2) A county or regional community action official shall:
12 (i) Coordinate school–based community forums, in cooperation with
13 local law enforcement officials; and
14 (ii) Conduct public relations efforts that include the following:
15 1. Parent contact;
16 2. Electronic media; and
17 3. Public service announcements.
18 [(e) (1) For fiscal year 2019, the Governor shall include an appropriation of at
19 least $3,000,000 in general funds in the State budget for the Department for the purpose
20 of awarding grants to county boards to implement the policy and conduct the training
21 required under this section.
22 (2) The Department shall disburse the grants authorized under paragraph
23 (1) of this subsection based on the enrollment count of students in public schools in the
24 State for the prior fiscal year.]
25 [(f)] (E) (1) On or before October 1 each year, each public school shall submit,
26 on the form that the Department requires, a report to the Department on each incident at
27 the school that required the use of naloxone or other OPIOID overdose–reversing
28 medication.
29 (2) The Department shall develop and disseminate a standard form to
30 report each incident requiring the use of naloxone or other OPIOID overdose–reversing
31 medication at a public school.

HOUSE BILL 222 5
1 [(3) On or before December 1, 2018, December 1, 2019, and December 1,
2 2020, the Department shall report the information provided under paragraph (1) of this
3 subsection to the General Assembly in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government
4 Article.]
5 11–1201.
6 (a) Except as provided in subsection (b) of this section, this subtitle applies only
7 to institutions of higher education in the State that receive operating or capital funding
8 from the State.
9 (b) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, this subtitle does
10 not apply to:
11 (i) The University of Maryland Global Campus;
12 (ii) The University of Maryland Center for Environmental Science;
13 or
14 (iii) An off–campus nonresidential location of an institution of higher
15 education.
16 (2) Each institution described under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall
17 provide all students with resources that alert and educate the students regarding heroin
18 and opioid addiction and prevention.
19 11–1202.
20 (a) Each institution of higher education shall establish a policy that addresses
21 heroin and opioid addiction and prevention.
22 (b) [The] SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION, THE policy
23 established under this subtitle shall require each institution to:
24 (1) Require incoming full–time students to participate in an in–person
25 heroin and opioid addiction and prevention awareness training, unless in–person training
26 is impracticable, then to participate in an electronic heroin and opioid addiction and
27 prevention awareness training;
28 (2) Provide incoming part–time students with resources that alert and
29 educate the students regarding heroin and opioid addiction and prevention; and
30 (3) Obtain and store at the institution naloxone or other OPIOID
31 overdose–reversing medication to be used in an emergency situation.

6 HOUSE BILL 222
1 (C) ANY TRAINING PROVIDED UNDER THE POLICY ESTABLISHED UNDER
2 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL INCLUDE INFORMATION ON THE
3 MITIGATING EFFECTS OF NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
4 MEDICATION.
5 11–1203.
6 (a) The policy established under this subtitle shall include:
7 (1) Training for campus police or other designated personnel on how to
8 recognize the symptoms of an opioid overdose;
9 (2) Procedures for the administration of naloxone or other OPIOID
10 overdose–reversing medications; [and]
11 (3) The proper follow–up emergency procedures; AND
12 (4) AUTHORIZATION FOR A STUDENT, A MEMBER OF THE
13 INSTITUTION’S STAFF, OR ANY LAWFULLY PRESENT INDIVIDUAL AT THE
14 INSTITUTION TO POSSESS NALOXONE OR OTHER OPIOID OVERDOSE–REVERSING
15 MEDICATION.
16 (b) Except for any willful or grossly negligent act, [campus police or other
17 designated personnel who have been trained under subsection (a)(1) of this section and who
18 respond] ANY INDIVIDUAL WHO RESPONDS in good faith to the overdose emergency of a
19 student, A STAFF MEMBER, OR ANY OTHER INDIVIDUAL LAWFULLY PRESENT in
20 accordance with this section may not be held personally liable for any act or omission in the
21 course of responding to the emergency.
22 11–1204.
23 [(a)] On or before October 1 each year, each institution of higher education shall
24 report to the Commission on each incident at the institution that required the use of
25 naloxone or other OPIOID overdose–reversing medication.
26 [(b) On or before December 1, 2018, December 1, 2019, and December 1, 2020, the
27 Commission shall report the information provided under subsection (a) of this section to
28 the General Assembly in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article.]
29 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
30 1, 2026.

